Using Disease Modelling to Inform Mitigation Efforts

Allison K Shaw, Lauren A White,
Matthew Michalska-Smith, Elizabeth T Borer,
Meggan E Craft, Eric W Seabloom,
Emilie Snell-Rood, & Michael Travisano

14 september 2020

Problem | Balancing public health and university function

Objectives | By the end of this lecture, you will be able to...

  1. Describe how to approach answering research questions with models
  2. Map mitigation/control measures onto model parameters
  3. Discuss how underlying assumptions and methodological choices affect the conclusions that can be drawn from model results

Case Study | UMN EEB department returning to work

Case Study | Research questions

  • How does returning to work affect the spread of disease
  • What are the important variables that influence this spread
  • How do we balance the inherent tradeoff between reducing COVID spread and the preserving economic activity
  • Are there modifications to how we have worked in the past to better navigate this tradeoff?


How to return to work safely?

Models | Letting your questions dictate your model

Models | Compartmental models



Models | ODE SEIR

  • tracks the proportion of the population in each class over time
  • considers the spread of disease in different “environments”
  • What are some of the limitations/assumptions you see in this model?

Models | ODE SEIR

  • Homogenous mixing
  • Some parameters are the same in all environments
  • Behavior doesn't change based on disease status
  • &c.

Models | Network chain binomial SEIR

  • Considers spatial configuration of people
  • Allows exploration of the structure of interpersonal interactions
  • What are some of the limitations of this way of representing the population?

Models | Network chain binomial SEIR

  • Doesn't contain common spaces
  • All shared spaces are equivalent risk of transmission
  • Network structure doesn't change based on disease status
  • &c.

Simulating Mitigation Efforts | Mapping interventions to parameters and vice versa

Simulating Mitigation | ODE SEIR

  • Time at work/commute/home (\(T_i\))
  • Fraction of population working (\(\theta\))
  • Transmission rate(s) (\(\beta_i\))
  • Latent period, recovery rate (\(\sigma\), \(\gamma\))

Simulating Mitigation | Network model

  • Transmission rate(s) (\(\beta_i\))
  • Latent period, recovery rate (\(\sigma\), \(\gamma\))
  • Limit types of work (change network structure)
